t12. The “Naked Face” Of Secular Exclusion: Bill 94 And The Privatization Of Belief -- t13. Religion And The Socio-Economic Integration Of Immigrants Across Canada -- tConclusion -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe place of religion in the public realm is the subject of frequent and lively debate in the media, among academics and policymakers, and within communities. With this edited collection, Solange Lefebvre and Lori G. Beaman bring together a series of case studies of religious groups and practices from all across Canada that re-examine and question the classic distinction between the public and private spheres.Religion in the Public Sphere explores the public image of religious groups, legal issues relating to “reasonable accommodations,” and the role of religion in public services and institutions like health care and education. Offering a wide range of contributions from religious studies, political science, theology, and law, Religion in the Public Sphere presents emerging new models to explain contemporary relations between religion, civil society, the private sector, family, and the state.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aReligion and lawxCase studiesxCanada. 0aReligion and lawzCanadavCase studies. 0aReligion and sociologyxCase studiesxCanada. 0aReligion and sociologyzCanadavCase studies. 0aReligion and statexCase studiesxCanada. 0aReligion and statezCanadavCase studies. 7aLAW / General.2bisacsh1 aAllen, Paul, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBanack, Clark, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBeaman, Lori G. , eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBeaman, Lori G., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vo